&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Union Government&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The Attorney General of India is the &lt;strong&gt;chief legal advisor to the Union Government&lt;/strong&gt; and is appointed by the President under Article 76 of the Indian Constitution.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;He/she represents the Union Government in all legal matters, including cases in the Supreme Court and High Courts.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The Attorney General provides legal advice to the government on matters of law and performs any other legal duties assigned by the President.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;While the Attorney General has the right to participate in Parliamentary proceedings, he/she does not have voting rights.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The Attorney General must be a person qualified to be appointed as a judge of the Supreme Court, i.e., with at least 10 years of experience as an advocate or a judge.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solicitor General of India&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Assists the Attorney General and represents the government in important legal cases.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Unlike the Attorney General, the Solicitor General does not provide advice directly to the government.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Advocate General of a State&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The Advocate General is the highest legal authority in a state and provides advice to the state government.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;He/she is appointed by the Governor under Article 165 of the Constitution.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Role of Attorney General in Constitutional Matters&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Acts as an advisor in constitutional disputes and government policies.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Provides guidance on issues like federalism and separation of powers.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Limitations of the Attorney General&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;He/she cannot defend any accused or oppose the government in legal matters.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The Attorney General is not a full-time employee of the government and can take up private legal practice, provided it does not conflict with official duties.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Rajasthan&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;According to Census 2011, Rajasthan recorded the &lt;strong&gt;highest difference in male and female literacy rates&lt;/strong&gt; among Indian states.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The male literacy rate in Rajasthan was approximately &lt;strong&gt;80.51%&lt;/strong&gt;, whereas the female literacy rate stood at &lt;strong&gt;52.66%&lt;/strong&gt;, creating a significant gap of &lt;strong&gt;27.85%&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This disparity highlights &lt;strong&gt;gender inequality&lt;/strong&gt; in education, particularly in rural areas of Rajasthan.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Efforts have been made by the state government through programs like &lt;strong&gt;Beti Bachao Beti Padhao&lt;/strong&gt; and Sarva Shiksha Abhiyan to bridge the literacy gap.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Rajasthan has historically faced challenges such as &lt;strong&gt;socio-cultural norms and lack of access to education for women&lt;/strong&gt;, contributing to this disparity.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Literacy Rate&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Literacy rate refers to the percentage of the population aged 7 years and above who can read and write with understanding.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is an essential indicator of a region&amp;#39;s social and economic development.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Gender Disparity in Literacy&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Gender disparity in literacy rates is caused by factors like traditional societal norms, poverty, and lack of access to education.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Government schemes such as &lt;strong&gt;Beti Bachao Beti Padhao&lt;/strong&gt; aim to reduce this disparity by promoting girl child education.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Census 2011&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Census 2011 is the 15th Indian Census conducted by the Registrar General and Census Commissioner of India.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It provides comprehensive data on population, literacy rates, employment, and housing conditions.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Schemes to Promote Literacy&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Samagra Shiksha Abhiyan:&lt;/strong&gt; Focuses on universal access to education and improving literacy rates.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Beti Bachao Beti Padhao:&lt;/strong&gt; Aims to improve gender equality in education and combat discrimination against girls.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Mura, daughter of a hunter&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;According to the Vishnu Purana, Chandragupta Maurya&amp;rsquo;s mother was &lt;strong&gt;Mura&lt;/strong&gt;, who was described as the daughter of a hunter.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Mura is often referred to as a woman of humble origin, whose lineage was tied to the &lt;strong&gt;Shudra class&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Chandragupta Maurya&amp;#39;s rise to power is frequently cited as an example of how individuals from lower social strata could ascend to great heights in ancient India.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Historical texts and puranas emphasize Chandragupta&amp;#39;s humble beginnings, which contributed to his perception as a transformative leader.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The Vishnu Purana, along with other ancient texts like the Buddhist chronicles, provides various accounts of Chandragupta&amp;rsquo;s ancestry, reflecting the diverse narratives surrounding his life.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Chandragupta Maurya:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;He was the founder of the Maurya Empire, which became one of the largest empires in ancient India.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Chandragupta was guided by his mentor, Chanakya, who authored the &lt;strong&gt;Arthashastra&lt;/strong&gt;, a treatise on governance and economics.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Under his reign, the Maurya Empire unified the Indian subcontinent and established a centralized administration.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Chandragupta later renounced his throne and adopted Jainism, spending his final years as an ascetic.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Vishnu Purana:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is one of the eighteen Mahapuranas, a genre of ancient Indian texts.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The Vishnu Purana provides genealogies of kings and stories of prominent figures like Chandragupta Maurya.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The Purana emphasizes the role of Vishnu in preserving dharma and cosmic order.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Chanakya&amp;rsquo;s Role:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Chanakya, also known as Kautilya, was the political advisor and strategist behind Chandragupta&amp;rsquo;s success.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;He played a pivotal role in overthrowing the Nanda dynasty and establishing the Maurya Empire.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Chanakya&amp;rsquo;s teachings in the Arthashastra include principles of governance, economics, and military strategy.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Social Stratification in Ancient India:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Ancient Indian society was divided into varnas (social classes), with Shudras typically occupying the lowest tier.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Chandragupta&amp;rsquo;s ascent challenged traditional notions of caste-based hierarchies.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Himachal Pradesh&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;As per Census 2011, Himachal Pradesh recorded the &lt;strong&gt;highest literacy rate among northern states&lt;/strong&gt; with a literacy rate of 82.80%.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Himachal Pradesh&amp;#39;s focus on education policies and rural literacy programs played a key role in achieving this milestone.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The literacy rate for males in Himachal Pradesh stood at 89.53%, while for females it was 75.93%, showcasing efforts toward &lt;strong&gt;gender inclusivity in education&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The state invested heavily in primary education and teacher training programs to improve its literacy rate.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Himachal Pradesh ranks &lt;strong&gt;11th overall in literacy rates&lt;/strong&gt; across India as per Census 2011 data.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Literacy Rate Definition:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Literacy rate refers to the percentage of people aged 7 and above who can read and write with understanding.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Census 2011 classified literacy into male and female literacy rates to assess gender disparity in education.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Key Focus Areas in Himachal Pradesh:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Emphasis on universal primary education and mid-day meal schemes to boost enrolment.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Implementation of adult literacy programs to bridge gaps in literacy among older age groups.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Strengthening of infrastructure like schools and libraries in rural areas.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Comparison with Other Northern States:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Punjab (76.68%) and Uttarakhand (78.82%) follow Himachal Pradesh but lag behind in overall literacy rate.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Haryana&amp;rsquo;s literacy rate stood at 75.55%, significantly lower compared to Himachal Pradesh.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;National Literacy Rate (Census 2011):&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The overall literacy rate of India was 74.04% in 2011, with Kerala leading at 93.91%.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Himachal Pradesh&amp;rsquo;s literacy rate was above the national average, showcasing its focus on educational reforms.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;PM Rashtriya Krishi Vikas Yojana&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;PM Rashtriya Krishi Vikas Yojana (RKVY)&lt;/strong&gt; aims to achieve food security, sustainable agriculture, and self-sufficiency by promoting growth in the agricultural sector.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It is a state plan scheme launched in 2007 but restructured as &lt;strong&gt;RKVY-Remunerative Approaches for Agriculture and Allied sector Rejuvenation (RKVY-RAFTAAR)&lt;/strong&gt; in 2017 to focus on pre- and post-harvest infrastructure.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Under this scheme, funds are provided to states as grants for agricultural development, ensuring decentralization and flexibility for local needs.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The scheme also supports innovation and technology adoption in agriculture to increase productivity and profitability for farmers.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It aligns with the government&amp;#39;s goal of doubling farmers&amp;#39; incomes by 2024, with a focus on value addition, market linkages, and sustainable farming practices.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Sustainable Agriculture&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It involves practices that maintain soil health, conserve water, and reduce dependency on chemical inputs.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Techniques include crop rotation, organic farming, integrated pest management, and agroforestry.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Sustainable agriculture ensures long-term productivity while minimizing environmental harm.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;National Food Security Mission (NFSM)&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Launched in 2007-08, it aims to increase the production of rice, wheat, pulses, and coarse cereals to meet the growing demand.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It focuses on area expansion, productivity enhancement, and restoring soil fertility.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The mission operates through cluster demonstrations, distribution of quality seeds, and resource conservation technologies.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;National Mission on Oilseeds and Oil Palm (NMOOP)&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It was launched in 2014-15 to augment the production of edible oils by promoting oilseeds and oil palm cultivation.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The mission aims to achieve self-sufficiency in edible oil production and reduce dependency on imports.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It emphasizes increasing the area under cultivation, improving productivity, and adopting high-yielding varieties.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Krishi Infrastructure Fund&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Launched in 2020, it provides financial support for building post-harvest infrastructure and community farming assets.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The fund has a corpus of Rs. 1 lakh crore, focusing on storage, processing, and value-addition facilities.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It empowers farmers and Farmer Producer Organizations (FPOs) to gain better market access and reduce wastage.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Folk Music&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Padmashree Mukund Nayak is a celebrated folk artist from Jharkhand, known for his contributions to the &lt;strong&gt;folk music traditions of the state&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;He was honoured with the prestigious &lt;strong&gt;Sangeet Natak Akademi Award&lt;/strong&gt; in 2017 for his exceptional contributions to &lt;strong&gt;folk music&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The award is India&amp;rsquo;s highest recognition given to practicing artists for their outstanding work in various performing arts categories, including music, dance, and theater.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Mukund Nayak has worked extensively to preserve and promote the &lt;strong&gt;Karma folk tradition&lt;/strong&gt;, a cultural heritage of Jharkhand.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;His efforts in bringing Jharkhand&amp;#39;s folk music to national recognition have greatly contributed to the preservation of indigenous art forms.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Sangeet Natak Akademi Awards:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Established in 1952, these awards are conferred annually by the Sangeet Natak Akademi, India&amp;#39;s National Academy for Music, Dance, and Drama.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The awards recognize outstanding achievements in various performing arts categories such as classical music, folk music, dance, and theater.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Recipients receive a cash prize, a citation, and a tamrapatra (copper plaque).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Karma Folk Tradition:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Karma is a popular folk dance and music tradition practiced predominantly in Jharkhand, Odisha, Chhattisgarh, and Madhya Pradesh.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It celebrates nature and the harvest season, performed during the Karma festival.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The music involves traditional instruments like the mandar, nagara, and flute.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Padmashree Award:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is the fourth highest civilian award in India, given for distinguished contributions in various fields such as art, literature, education, sports, and social service.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Mukund Nayak was awarded the Padmashree for his contributions to folk music and cultural preservation.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Preservation of Folk Music:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Folk music reflects the cultural heritage and traditions of a region, passed down orally through generations.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Efforts to preserve folk music include documentation, performances, and integration into mainstream platforms.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Artists like Mukund Nayak play a crucial role in safeguarding these traditions against the rapid modernization of society.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;November&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;Rann Utsav&lt;/strong&gt; is an annual cultural festival celebrated in the Rann of Kutch, Gujarat.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It begins in the month of &lt;strong&gt;November&lt;/strong&gt; and continues until February, showcasing the vibrant culture, crafts, and traditions of Gujarat.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The festival is organized by the Gujarat Tourism Department and attracts tourists from across the globe.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Key attractions include the &lt;strong&gt;white salt desert&lt;/strong&gt;, folk music and dance performances, camel rides, adventure sports, and traditional Gujarati cuisine.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The event is held in Dhordo village, often referred to as the &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;Tent City&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; due to its luxurious tent accommodations.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Rann of Kutch&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The Rann of Kutch is a seasonal salt marsh located in the Thar Desert in Gujarat.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It spans an area of approximately 7,500 square kilometers, making it one of the largest salt deserts in the world.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The region is known for its unique geography, biodiversity, and cultural significance.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Significance of Rann Utsav&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The festival highlights the art, craft, and cultural heritage of Gujarat.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It boosts tourism and contributes significantly to the local economy.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It provides a platform for artisans and performers to showcase their talent and promote indigenous crafts.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Activities at Rann Utsav&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Adventure activities such as paramotoring, ATV rides, and hot air ballooning are popular among visitors.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Shopping for handmade crafts, jewelry, and textiles is a key attraction.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Visitors can enjoy stargazing, as the desert offers clear night skies.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Best Time to Visit&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The ideal time to attend Rann Utsav is between November and February when the weather is pleasant.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The full moon nights during the festival offer breathtaking views of the white desert illuminated by moonlight.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;One-and-a-half times the cost of production&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In the Union Budget for 2018-19, the government announced that the Minimum Support Price (MSP) for all principal crops would be set at &lt;strong&gt;one-and-a-half times (1.5x) the cost of production&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This decision aimed to ensure remunerative prices for farmers and address the issue of agrarian distress in the country.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The MSP calculation is based on the comprehensive cost of production, including expenses such as seeds, fertilizers, labor, irrigation, and other inputs.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The announcement was in line with the Swaminathan Commission&amp;#39;s recommendations, which advocated fixing MSP at least 50% higher than the cost of production.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The initiative was primarily targeted at improving farmers&amp;#39; income and boosting agricultural productivity in India.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Minimum Support Price (MSP):&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;MSP is a form of market intervention by the Government of India to safeguard farmers against sharp price falls during bumper production years.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The MSP is announced for 22 mandated crops and is determined by the Cabinet Committee on Economic Affairs (CCEA).&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is based on the recommendations of the Commission for Agricultural Costs and Prices (CACP).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Swaminathan Commission:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The National Commission on Farmers, chaired by Dr. M.S. Swaminathan, recommended fixing MSP at least 50% above the cost of production (C2).&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The formula includes both input costs (A2) and the imputed value of family labor (FL).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Types of Costs in MSP Calculation:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;A2:&lt;/strong&gt; Includes out-of-pocket expenses like seeds, fertilizers, and labor.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;A2+FL:&lt;/strong&gt; A2 costs plus the imputed value of unpaid family labor.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;C2:&lt;/strong&gt; Comprehensive cost, including A2+FL and the rental value of owned land and interest on fixed capital.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Implementation and Benefits:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The 1.5x MSP policy ensures better income for farmers and reduces their dependence on informal credit systems.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It also incentivizes crop diversification and adoption of sustainable farming practices.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;1951&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The First Five-Year Plan of India was launched in &lt;strong&gt;1951&lt;/strong&gt; and covered the period from 1951 to 1956.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It was based on the &lt;strong&gt;Harrod-Domar Model&lt;/strong&gt;, which emphasized investment and savings as the key to economic growth.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The primary focus of the First Five-Year Plan was on &lt;strong&gt;agriculture, irrigation, and energy&lt;/strong&gt; to address food shortages and boost rural development.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The plan aimed at achieving a growth rate of &lt;strong&gt;2.1%&lt;/strong&gt; annually, but India successfully achieved a growth rate of around &lt;strong&gt;3.6%&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The Planning Commission, established in &lt;strong&gt;1950&lt;/strong&gt;, was responsible for formulating and overseeing the implementation of the Five-Year Plans.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Five-Year Plans in India&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;India adopted the concept of centralized economic planning inspired by the Soviet Union.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The Planning Commission was established under the leadership of &lt;strong&gt;Prime Minister Jawaharlal Nehru&lt;/strong&gt; to implement the Five-Year Plans.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Each plan targeted specific sectors such as agriculture, industry, and social development based on national priorities.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The Five-Year Plans continued until &lt;strong&gt;2017&lt;/strong&gt;, when they were replaced by the &lt;strong&gt;NITI Aayog&amp;#39;s Three-Year Action Agenda&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Harrod-Domar Model&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This economic model emphasizes the importance of savings and investment in achieving economic growth.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The model assumes that economic growth is directly proportional to the savings rate and inversely proportional to the capital-output ratio.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It was used as a foundational framework for India&amp;#39;s First Five-Year Plan.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Planning Commission&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Established in &lt;strong&gt;1950&lt;/strong&gt;, the Planning Commission was tasked with assessing resources and formulating India&amp;#39;s Five-Year Plans.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The commission worked under the chairmanship of the Prime Minister and included experts from various fields.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It was replaced by &lt;strong&gt;NITI Aayog&lt;/strong&gt; in &lt;strong&gt;2015&lt;/strong&gt; to better align with contemporary needs.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Focus of the First Five-Year Plan&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The plan prioritized &lt;strong&gt;agriculture&lt;/strong&gt; due to severe food shortages in the post-independence period.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Key projects included the development of irrigation systems like the &lt;strong&gt;Bhakra Nangal Dam&lt;/strong&gt; and energy initiatives.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It also focused on land reforms and rural development to improve livelihoods in the countryside.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Cricket&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The &amp;quot;Timed Out&amp;quot; rule in cricket is outlined in the &lt;strong&gt;Marylebone Cricket Club (MCC) Laws of Cricket&lt;/strong&gt;, under Law 40.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This rule states that a new batter must be ready to face the next delivery or at the crease within &lt;strong&gt;three minutes&lt;/strong&gt; of the previous batter&amp;#39;s dismissal.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;If the incoming batter fails to arrive within the stipulated time, the fielding team can appeal to the umpire to declare the batter as &amp;quot;Timed Out.&amp;quot;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The &amp;quot;Timed Out&amp;quot; rule is a rare mode of dismissal and emphasizes maintaining the pace and flow of the game.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This rule applies to all formats of cricket, including &lt;strong&gt;Test matches, One-Day Internationals (ODIs), and Twenty20 (T20) matches&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Rare Dismissal Modes in Cricket:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Other rare modes of dismissal in cricket include &lt;strong&gt;Hit Wicket&lt;/strong&gt;, &lt;strong&gt;Obstructing the Field&lt;/strong&gt;, &lt;strong&gt;Handling the Ball&lt;/strong&gt; (now included under Obstructing the Field), and &lt;strong&gt;Retired Out&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;These dismissals occur infrequently in professional matches compared to common methods like bowled, caught, or LBW.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Historical Instances of Timed Out:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The first recorded instance of a &amp;quot;Timed Out&amp;quot; dismissal in first-class cricket occurred in 1987 when Andrew Jordaan was dismissed in South Africa&amp;#39;s domestic competition.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;There have been very few instances of this dismissal in professional cricket, making it one of the rarest ways to lose a wicket.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Purpose of the Rule:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The rule ensures that the game maintains its rhythm and prevents unnecessary delays caused by players taking excessive time to get ready.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It also serves to uphold the spirit of the game by emphasizing punctuality and readiness among players.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Recent Updates to MCC Laws:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The MCC regularly updates the Laws of Cricket to address evolving scenarios and ensure fairness in the game.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The 2022 Code of Laws included revisions to clarify several rules, including &amp;quot;Timed Out,&amp;quot; to ensure better understanding and implementation.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Padma Shri&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Ramlal Bareth&lt;/strong&gt;, an 87-year-old Kathak dancer, is the last surviving exponent of the Raigarh court&amp;#39;s classical dance tradition.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;He was recognized with the &lt;strong&gt;Padma Shri award in 2024&lt;/strong&gt; for his contributions to Indian classical dance.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;Padma Shri&lt;/strong&gt; is India&amp;#39;s fourth-highest civilian award, given for distinguished achievements in various fields such as arts, literature, sports, and social service.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Ramlal Bareth has dedicated decades to preserving and promoting Kathak, a classical dance form renowned for storytelling through intricate footwork and expressions.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;His recognition highlights the importance of preserving India&amp;#39;s rich cultural heritage and honoring its traditional art forms.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Kathak Dance:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Kathak is one of the eight classical dance forms of India, originating from the northern regions.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The term &amp;quot;Kathak&amp;quot; is derived from &amp;quot;Katha,&amp;quot; meaning story, as it involves storytelling through dance.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is characterized by intricate footwork, spins, and expressive gestures, often accompanied by Hindustani classical music.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Historically, Kathak was performed in temples and later evolved under Mughal patronage, blending Hindu and Persian influences.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Raigarh Court&amp;#39;s Contribution:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The Raigarh princely state was a notable patron of arts, especially classical dance and music.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It played a significant role in nurturing Kathak and ensuring its growth as a respected art form.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The court&amp;#39;s dancers and musicians contributed to the development of unique styles and compositions.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Padma Awards:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Instituted in 1954, the Padma Awards are classified into Padma Vibhushan, Padma Bhushan, and Padma Shri.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Padma Shri is awarded for distinguished service in any field, including arts, literature, sports, and public service.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The awards are announced annually on Republic Day and are conferred by the President of India.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Preserving Cultural Heritage:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Honoring artists like Ramlal Bareth underscores the importance of safeguarding India&amp;#39;s classical art forms.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Government initiatives such as Sangeet Natak Akademi and cultural awards play a key role in supporting traditional arts.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Awareness and education about classical dance forms help promote cultural continuity among younger generations.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Use of modern irrigation techniques&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The Green Revolution introduced advanced agricultural practices, including the use of &lt;strong&gt;modern irrigation techniques&lt;/strong&gt; like drip and sprinkler systems for water conservation.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Modern irrigation methods ensured &lt;strong&gt;efficient utilization of water resources&lt;/strong&gt; and helped increase crop yields, especially in areas with scarce water supply.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;These techniques supported the cultivation of high-yield variety (HYV) crops, which required &lt;strong&gt;timely and adequate water supply&lt;/strong&gt; for optimal growth.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The adoption of modern irrigation systems reduced dependency on &lt;strong&gt;monsoon rainfall&lt;/strong&gt;, making agriculture more resilient to climate variability.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Modern irrigation played a critical role in transforming India&amp;rsquo;s agricultural sector during the Green Revolution, contributing to &lt;strong&gt;food security and self-sufficiency&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;High-Yield Variety (HYV) Seeds:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;HYV seeds were developed to produce higher output per hectare compared to traditional seeds.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;These seeds often required proper irrigation, fertilizers, and pesticides for maximum productivity.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Chemical Fertilizers and Pesticides:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The Green Revolution encouraged the use of chemical fertilizers to enhance soil fertility and crop production.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Pesticides were introduced to protect crops from pests and diseases, ensuring a more stable yield.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Mechanization of Agriculture:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Tractors, harvesters, and other machinery replaced traditional animal labor, significantly improving efficiency.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Mechanization allowed large-scale farming and reduced manual labor dependency.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Impact on Food Security:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The Green Revolution helped India achieve self-sufficiency in food grains, reducing dependency on imports.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It significantly contributed to reducing hunger and malnutrition in the country.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Environmental Concerns:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Excessive use of fertilizers and pesticides caused soil degradation and water pollution.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Modern irrigation techniques, though efficient, sometimes led to waterlogging and salinization in certain areas.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Siltation&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Siltation&lt;/strong&gt; refers to the process by which fine particles like silt and sediment accumulate in water bodies, leading to pollution and degradation of aquatic ecosystems.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This type of pollution occurs due to activities like &lt;strong&gt;deforestation, mining, and construction&lt;/strong&gt; that increase erosion and sediment runoff.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Siltation can disrupt aquatic habitats by &lt;strong&gt;blocking sunlight penetration&lt;/strong&gt;, reducing oxygen levels, and smothering organisms living on the seabed or riverbed.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It also affects water quality and can &lt;strong&gt;reduce the capacity of reservoirs, lakes, and rivers&lt;/strong&gt;, impacting human activities such as irrigation and hydroelectric power generation.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Preventive measures include &lt;strong&gt;soil conservation practices&lt;/strong&gt;, afforestation, and the use of sediment control techniques to reduce erosion.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Suspended solids:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;They are small solid particles that remain in water due to turbulence or slow settling rates.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Sources include agricultural runoff, industrial discharge, and urban stormwater.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Excessive suspended solids can lead to turbidity, reducing light penetration and affecting aquatic photosynthesis.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Impact of siltation:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Damages aquatic ecosystems by burying habitats and reducing biodiversity.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Causes economic losses by reducing the efficiency of water infrastructure such as reservoirs and dams.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Can lead to increased flooding due to reduced channel capacity.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Soil erosion:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;A major contributor to siltation, caused by deforestation, overgrazing, and improper land management.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Erosion control measures include terracing, planting vegetation, and using sediment barriers.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Other types of water pollution:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Thermal pollution:&lt;/strong&gt; Caused by the discharge of heated water, impacting aquatic life.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Microbiological pollution:&lt;/strong&gt; Involves harmful pathogens entering water, affecting human and animal health.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Nutrient pollution:&lt;/strong&gt; Excess nitrogen and phosphorus lead to eutrophication, depleting oxygen levels in water bodies.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Jharkhand&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Droupadi Murmu&lt;/strong&gt; served as the &lt;strong&gt;9th Governor of Jharkhand&lt;/strong&gt; from May 18, 2015, to July 12, 2021.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;She was the &lt;strong&gt;first tribal woman&lt;/strong&gt; to be appointed as the Governor of Jharkhand since the state&amp;#39;s formation in 2000.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;During her tenure, she was known for her work in &lt;strong&gt;tribal welfare&lt;/strong&gt; and governance in the state.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Her appointment as the Governor was widely seen as a recognition of her contributions to public service and her commitment to social causes.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;She has now become the &lt;strong&gt;15th President of India&lt;/strong&gt;, making history as the first tribal woman to hold this prestigious position.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Governorship in India:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The Governor is the &lt;strong&gt;constitutional head of a state&lt;/strong&gt;, appointed by the President of India for a term of five years.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The Governor acts as the &lt;strong&gt;representative of the central government&lt;/strong&gt; in the state.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Key responsibilities include giving assent to bills, summoning or dissolving the state legislature, and overseeing the functioning of the state government.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Jharkhand:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Jharkhand is a state in eastern India, carved out of Bihar in &lt;strong&gt;2000&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is rich in natural resources and is known for its tribal culture and traditions.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The state has a significant tribal population, comprising around &lt;strong&gt;26% of its total population&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Droupadi Murmu&amp;rsquo;s Background:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;She hails from the &lt;strong&gt;Santhal tribal community&lt;/strong&gt; in Odisha.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;She began her political career as a member of the &lt;strong&gt;Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP)&lt;/strong&gt; and served in various capacities in Odisha, including as a minister.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Her rise to becoming the President of India is a &lt;strong&gt;landmark achievement&lt;/strong&gt; for tribal representation in Indian politics.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Role as President of India:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The President is the &lt;strong&gt;head of state&lt;/strong&gt; and the supreme commander of the armed forces in India.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The President&amp;#39;s role is largely ceremonial, but they have significant powers in times of political crises, such as the dissolution of Lok Sabha or the imposition of President&amp;#39;s Rule in a state.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;As President, Droupadi Murmu has emphasized &lt;strong&gt;inclusive development&lt;/strong&gt; and the empowerment of marginalized communities.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Law of Refraction&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Willebrord Snell, a Dutch mathematician and astronomer, formulated the &lt;strong&gt;Law of Refraction&lt;/strong&gt;, commonly known as Snell&amp;#39;s Law, in 1621.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Snell&amp;#39;s Law&lt;/strong&gt; mathematically describes how light bends when it passes from one medium to another with different refractive indices.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The law is expressed as &lt;strong&gt;n‚ÇÅsin&amp;theta;‚ÇÅ = n‚ÇÇsin&amp;theta;‚ÇÇ&lt;/strong&gt;, where n‚ÇÅ and n‚ÇÇ are the refractive indices of the two media, and &amp;theta;‚ÇÅ and &amp;theta;‚ÇÇ are the angles of incidence and refraction respectively.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This discovery is fundamental to the field of optics and is widely used in designing lenses, optical instruments, and understanding light behavior.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The law also underpins modern technologies such as fiber optics, laser systems, and imaging devices.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Refraction:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Refraction is the bending of light as it passes from one transparent medium to another due to a change in its speed.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is governed by the refractive index, which is a measure of how much light slows down in a medium compared to a vacuum.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Applications include magnifying glasses, cameras, telescopes, and corrective lenses.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Refractive Index:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The refractive index is a dimensionless number indicating the ratio of the speed of light in a vacuum to its speed in a given medium.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It determines how much light will bend when transitioning between materials.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Common values: Air (&amp;asymp;1), Water (&amp;asymp;1.33), Glass (&amp;asymp;1.5).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Critical Angle and Total Internal Reflection:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The critical angle is the angle of incidence above which light is entirely reflected within a medium, rather than refracted.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Total internal reflection is a phenomenon used in fiber optics and diamond brilliance.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Applications of Snell&amp;#39;s Law:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Fiber optic communication systems rely on controlled refraction and total internal reflection.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is essential in lens design for cameras, microscopes, and telescopes.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Understanding atmospheric refraction helps explain phenomena like mirages and the apparent bending of starlight.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Gorges&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Gorges&lt;/strong&gt; are deep, narrow valleys with steep sides, typically formed by the erosional activity of a river in its upper course.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;These are created due to the river cutting vertically into the bedrock as it flows downhill with high energy, carving out steep walls over time.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Gorges are most commonly formed in areas with resistant rock, where the river&amp;#39;s erosive power is greater than the resistance of the rock.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The formation of a gorge is a characteristic feature of a river&amp;#39;s youthful stage, where it flows rapidly down steep gradients.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Examples include the Kali Gandaki Gorge in Nepal and the Grand Canyon in the USA, both of which highlight the erosive power of rivers over millennia.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Upper Course of a River:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is the first stage of a river&amp;rsquo;s journey, typically found in mountainous or hilly regions.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Rivers in this stage have high velocity and energy, leading to vertical erosion and the formation of features like gorges, waterfalls, and rapids.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Other Features of a River&amp;#39;s Upper Course:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Waterfalls:&lt;/strong&gt; Sudden drops in a river&amp;#39;s course, often formed where hard rock overlays softer rock.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Rapids:&lt;/strong&gt; Sections of turbulent, fast-flowing water caused by a steep gradient or obstacles in the riverbed.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Meanders and Floodplains:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;These are features of the river&amp;#39;s middle and lower courses where the flow is slower, and lateral erosion and deposition dominate.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Unlike gorges, meanders and floodplains are absent in the upper course due to high energy and steep gradients.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Oxbow Lakes:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;These are U-shaped water bodies formed from abandoned meanders in the lower course of a river.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Their formation occurs due to sediment deposition cutting off a meander loop from the main river channel.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Kuchipudi&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Kuchipudi&lt;/strong&gt; is a classical dance form originating from &lt;strong&gt;Kuchelapuram village&lt;/strong&gt; in Krishna district of Andhra Pradesh, India.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It was developed as a form of &lt;strong&gt;dance-drama&lt;/strong&gt; combining music, acting, and movement, which is unique among Indian classical dance forms.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The dance form is named after its place of origin, &lt;strong&gt;Kuchelapuram&lt;/strong&gt;, and traditionally performed by male Brahmin priests.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Kuchipudi performances often depict stories from Hindu mythology, especially the &lt;strong&gt;Ramayana, Mahabharata, and Puranas&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Over time, Kuchipudi transitioned into a refined classical art form, incorporating &lt;strong&gt;intricate footwork, graceful movements, and expressive storytelling.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Origin and Development:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Kuchipudi originated in the 3rd century BCE, but its codified form emerged in the 17th century under Siddhendra Yogi.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Siddhendra Yogi is considered the father of Kuchipudi and refined it into a structured art form.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Performance Style:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is characterized by rapid footwork, dramatic expression, and rhythmic patterns.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Performers often combine singing and acting with dancing, making it a holistic art form.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Costumes and Makeup:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Kuchipudi dancers wear vibrant costumes, intricate jewelry, and expressive makeup to enhance their storytelling.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The attire varies based on the character being portrayed, such as gods, demons, or humans.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Modern Adaptations:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;While Kuchipudi was historically performed by men, today, women also actively participate and dominate the art form.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Contemporary Kuchipudi performances often include solo dances, which were rare in traditional formats.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Three lists&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The Government of India Act, 1935 introduced a federal structure with a division of powers between the central government (federation) and provinces through &lt;strong&gt;three legislative lists&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The three lists were categorized as &lt;strong&gt;Federal List&lt;/strong&gt;, &lt;strong&gt;Provincial List&lt;/strong&gt;, and &lt;strong&gt;Concurrent List&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Federal List&lt;/strong&gt; included subjects under the exclusive jurisdiction of the central government such as defense, foreign affairs, and railways.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Provincial List&lt;/strong&gt; contained subjects under the provincial governments, including police, public health, and education.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Concurrent List&lt;/strong&gt; covered subjects where both the center and provinces could legislate, such as criminal law and marriage.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Government of India Act, 1935:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It was the longest and most detailed legislation ever passed by the British Parliament for India.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The Act introduced provincial autonomy, allowing provinces to function as autonomous administrative units.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It provided for the establishment of a Federal Court to resolve disputes between provinces and the federation.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The Act also proposed the creation of an All-India Federation, but it never came into effect due to lack of agreement among princely states.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Concurrent List:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The concept of a concurrent list was introduced for the first time in Indian legislative history by the 1935 Act.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It laid the foundation for cooperative federalism in India, later adopted in the Constitution of India (1950).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Impact on Indian Constitution:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The Government of India Act, 1935 served as an important blueprint for the drafting of the Indian Constitution.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Many features such as division of powers, bicameralism, and federal structure were adopted and refined in the Indian Constitution.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Key Terminology:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Federalism:&lt;/strong&gt; A system of governance where power is divided between central and regional authorities.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Provincial Autonomy:&lt;/strong&gt; The ability of provinces to govern themselves independently within certain areas.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;55 m&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The standard width of a hockey field for international matches is &lt;strong&gt;55 meters&lt;/strong&gt;, as per the regulations set by the International Hockey Federation (FIH).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The field is rectangular, with a length of &lt;strong&gt;91.4 meters&lt;/strong&gt; and a width of &lt;strong&gt;55 meters&lt;/strong&gt;, ensuring uniformity in competitive play.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The field is divided into halves, each featuring a &lt;strong&gt;23-meter line&lt;/strong&gt; that helps demarcate key playing zones.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The dimensions are strictly maintained to support fair gameplay and adherence to international standards.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The goalposts are placed at the center of each width side, with standardized dimensions to align with the field size.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Field Markings:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The field includes distinct markings such as the &lt;strong&gt;23-meter line, penalty spot, and shooting circle&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The shooting circle is a &lt;strong&gt;D-shaped area&lt;/strong&gt; around the goal, where attacking players can score.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Surface Type:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;International hockey matches are generally played on &lt;strong&gt;synthetic turf&lt;/strong&gt;, which ensures consistent ball movement and player traction.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Natural grass was traditionally used but is now rare due to maintenance challenges and uneven play.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Goal Dimensions:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The goal width is &lt;strong&gt;3.66 meters&lt;/strong&gt;, and the height is &lt;strong&gt;2.14 meters&lt;/strong&gt;, standardized for all international matches.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The goalposts are equipped with nets to catch the ball securely after scoring.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Regulatory Body:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;International Hockey Federation (FIH)&lt;/strong&gt; is responsible for setting and enforcing field dimensions and other rules globally.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;FIH regulations ensure uniform standards across international tournaments.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Bombay Session&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The Quit India Resolution was passed during the &lt;strong&gt;Bombay Session of the Indian National Congress&lt;/strong&gt; held on &lt;strong&gt;8 August 1942&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This session was presided over by &lt;strong&gt;Maulana Abul Kalam Azad&lt;/strong&gt;, who was the President of the Indian National Congress at the time.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The resolution, also known as the &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;August Kranti&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt;, marked the beginning of the Quit India Movement against British rule in India.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The movement called for immediate independence of India and was characterized by the slogan &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;Do or Die&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt;, given by Mahatma Gandhi.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The British government reacted swiftly by arresting top Congress leaders, including Mahatma Gandhi, Jawaharlal Nehru, and Sardar Patel, effectively crippling the movement&amp;#39;s leadership.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Quit India Movement (1942):&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It was a mass protest demanding an end to British rule in India during World War II.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The movement was non-violent in principle but saw instances of violent clashes with the British authorities.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The British government described it as the most serious revolt since the 1857 uprising.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Despite the suppression, it significantly strengthened Indian unity and paved the way for independence in 1947.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Key Leaders:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Although Mahatma Gandhi was the central figure, other leaders like Jawaharlal Nehru, Sardar Patel, and Aruna Asaf Ali played vital roles.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Aruna Asaf Ali became known as the &amp;quot;Heroine of the Quit India Movement&amp;quot; for hoisting the Congress flag at the Gowalia Tank Maidan in Bombay.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Significance of the Bombay Session:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The session demonstrated the Indian National Congress&amp;#39;s unified demand for complete independence.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It marked a shift from earlier demands for dominion status to a clear call for outright independence.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Impact on British Rule:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The movement created immense pressure on the British, who had to divert resources during World War II to suppress the unrest in India.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It showcased the Indian people&amp;#39;s determination for self-rule and contributed to the eventual withdrawal of British rule in 1947.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Given:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Cost Price (C.P.) = 100 (Assume for simplicity)&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Mark Price (M.P.) = 20% above C.P. = 100 + 20% of 100 = 100 + 20 = 120&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Discount = 20% of M.P. = 20% of 120 = 24&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Selling Price (S.P.) = M.P. - Discount = 120 - 24 = 96&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Formula Used:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Profit or Loss Percentage = [(S.P. - C.P.) / C.P.] &amp;times; 100&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Calculation:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;S.P. = 96, C.P. = 100&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Profit or Loss = S.P. - C.P. = 96 - 100 = -4 (Negative indicates loss)&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Loss Percentage = [(Loss) / C.P.] &amp;times; 100&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;rArr; Loss Percentage = [(-4) / 100] &amp;times; 100&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;rArr; Loss Percentage = -4%&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Therefore, the Loss Percentage is 4%.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Given:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Cost Price (C.P.) = ‚Çπ500&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Profit Percentage = 28%&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Formula Used:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Selling Price (S.P.) = C.P. &amp;times; (1 + Profit Percentage / 100)&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Calculation:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;S.P. = 500 &amp;times; (1 + 28 / 100)&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;rArr; S.P. = 500 &amp;times; (1 + 0.28)&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;rArr; S.P. = 500 &amp;times; 1.28&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;rArr; S.P. = 640&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The shopkeeper should sell the article at ‚Çπ640 to make a 28% profit.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Given:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Total amount to be divided = ‚Çπ4,800&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Ratio among Ram, Shyam, and Kartik = 4 : 8 : 3&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Formula Used:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Amount received by each = (Individual&amp;#39;s ratio / Sum of ratios) &amp;times; Total amount&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Calculation:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Sum of ratios = 4 + 8 + 3&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;rArr; Sum of ratios = 15&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Amount received by Shyam = (Shyam&amp;#39;s ratio / Sum of ratios) &amp;times; Total amount&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;rArr; Amount received by Shyam = (8 / 15) &amp;times; ‚Çπ4,800&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;rArr; Amount received by Shyam = ‚Çπ(8 &amp;times; 4,800) / 15&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;rArr; Amount received by Shyam = ‚Çπ38,400 / 15&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;rArr; Amount received by Shyam = ‚Çπ2,560&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Therefore, the amount received by Shyam is ‚Çπ2,560.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Given:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Total amount Mahesh has = ‚Çπ1617&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Rate of interest = 10% compounded annually&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Vijay&amp;#39;s investment period = 15 years&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Ajay&amp;#39;s investment period = 16 years&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Vijay and Ajay received the same amount after their respective investment periods.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Formula Used:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Compound Interest Formula: A = P(1 + r/100)&lt;sup&gt;t&lt;/sup&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Where:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;A = Final amount&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;P = Principal amount&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;r = Rate of interest&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;t = Time (in years)&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Calculation:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Let Mahesh give Vijay ‚Çπx and Ajay ‚Çπ(1617 - x).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;According to the question, the final amounts for Vijay and Ajay are equal:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;x(1 + 10/100)&lt;sup&gt;15&lt;/sup&gt; = (1617 - x)(1 + 10/100)&lt;sup&gt;16&lt;/sup&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;rArr; x(1.1)&lt;sup&gt;15&lt;/sup&gt; = (1617 - x)(1.1)&lt;sup&gt;16&lt;/sup&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;rArr; x = (1617 - x)(1.1)&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;rArr; x = 1617 &amp;times; 1.1 - x &amp;times; 1.1&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;rArr; x + 1.1x = 1617 &amp;times; 1.1&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;rArr; 2.1x = 1778.7&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;rArr; x = 1778.7 / 2.1&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;rArr; x = 847&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Mahesh gave Vijay ‚Çπ847.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

