	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;Transparent&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; refers to something that allows light to pass through so that objects behind can be clearly seen. (‡§™‡§æ‡§∞‡§¶‡§∞‡•ç‡§∂‡•Ä)
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; The &lt;strong&gt;transparent &lt;/strong&gt;plastic sheet allowed us to see the contents inside the package.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Hence, we can infer that the opposite of &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;Opaque&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; is &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;Transparent&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is: &lt;strong&gt;Transparent&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Here are the other options explained along with their Hindi meanings and example sentences:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Cloudy&lt;/strong&gt; (&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;‡§ß‡•Å‡§Ç‡§ß‡§≤‡§æ&lt;/span&gt;): Not clear or transparent; filled with clouds or resembling a cloud.

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; The sky was &lt;strong&gt;cloudy &lt;/strong&gt;before the heavy rain started.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Dull&lt;/strong&gt; (&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;‡§Æ‡§Ç‡§¶&lt;/span&gt;): Lacking brightness or vividness; not lively.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; The &lt;strong&gt;dull &lt;/strong&gt;surface of the old mirror made it hard to see reflections.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Dark&lt;/strong&gt; (&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;‡§Ö‡§Ç‡§ß‡§ï‡§æ‡§∞‡§Æ‡§Ø&lt;/span&gt;): Having little or no light; black or deep in colour.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; The room was &lt;strong&gt;dark &lt;/strong&gt;after the power outage.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;on&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The context indicates a regular activity carried out by Sarah and Tom during their free time, specifically over the weekend.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct preposition to indicate this regular weekend activity is &amp;quot;on.&amp;quot;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Other options (&amp;quot;before,&amp;quot; &amp;quot;during,&amp;quot; &amp;quot;in&amp;quot;) do not fit the context of specifying time accurately and appropriately in this sentence.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;Option 1&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;Complete Passage:&lt;i&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;em&gt;Sarah and Tom love to go to the park &lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;on&lt;/u&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;weekends. Last Sunday, they (2) ________ a picnic basket with sandwiches, fruit, and juice. They (3) _________ a blanket to sit on and a frisbee to play with.&lt;/em&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;As soon as (4) ________ at the park, Sarah spread the blanket on the green grass. They enjoyed their sandwiches and had juicy oranges. After eating, (5) __________ to play with the frisbee.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Before &lt;/strong&gt;(‡§™‡§π‡§≤‡•á): &amp;quot;Before&amp;quot; indicates a previous time or earlier than a specific point, which does not fit accurately in this context.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;During &lt;/strong&gt;(‡§ï‡•á ‡§¶‡•å‡§∞‡§æ‡§®): &amp;quot;During&amp;quot; indicates a period of time in which something occurs, but it is not suitable for indicating a specific time at which an activity is done regularly.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;In &lt;/strong&gt;(‡§Æ‡•á‡§Ç): &amp;quot;In&amp;quot; can be used to indicate a period of time or a general sense of being inside a place, but it is incorrect for specifying weekends specifically.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;arranged&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The sentence describes how Sarah and Tom prepared their picnic basket by putting different food items in order.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The verb &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;arranged&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; fits best here as it suggests that they carefully placed the sandwiches, fruit, and juice in the basket in an organized way.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;While &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;packed&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; is also a close fit, the focus here is more on neat organization rather than simply stuffing items, making &amp;quot;arranged&amp;quot; more precise.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Options like &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;gathered&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; and &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;accumulated&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; imply collecting items but do not reflect the sense of thoughtful placement.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;Option 2&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;Complete Passage:&lt;i&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;em style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;Sarah and Tom love to go to the park&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;on&lt;/u&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;weekends. Last Sunday, they &lt;/em&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;arranged&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;em style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt; a picnic basket with sandwiches, fruit, and juice. They (3) _________ a blanket to sit on and a frisbee to play with.&lt;/em&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;As soon as (4) ________ at the park, Sarah spread the blanket on the green grass. They enjoyed their sandwiches and had juicy oranges. After eating, (5) __________ to play with the frisbee.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Gathered &lt;/strong&gt;(‡§è‡§ï‡§§‡•ç‡§∞ ‡§ï‡§ø‡§Ø‡§æ): Means to collect, not necessarily to organize neatly in a basket.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Packed &lt;/strong&gt;(‡§™‡•à‡§ï ‡§ï‡§ø‡§Ø‡§æ): Implies stuffing or filling, but may miss the nuance of careful placement.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Accumulated &lt;/strong&gt;(‡§∏‡§Ç‡§ó‡•ç‡§∞‡§π‡§ø‡§§ ‡§ï‡§ø‡§Ø‡§æ): Refers to collecting over time, not suitable in the picnic context.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;brought&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The sentence talks about carrying items like a blanket and a frisbee to the park for a picnic.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The verb required here should indicate the action of taking items from home to another place, which is perfectly expressed by &amp;quot;brought&amp;quot;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;Brought&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; is the past tense of &amp;quot;bring&amp;quot; and is the correct word to describe carrying something along to a location.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Other options like &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;buy&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; (purchase), &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;manage&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; (handle or control), and &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;arrange&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; (organize) do not fit the context of carrying picnic items to a park.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;Option 3&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;Complete Passage:&lt;i&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;em style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;Sarah and Tom love to go to the park&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;on&lt;/u&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;weekends. Last Sunday, they&amp;nbsp;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;em style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;arranged&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&amp;nbsp;a picnic basket with sandwiches, fruit, and juice. They &lt;/em&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;brought&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;em style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt; a blanket to sit on and a frisbee to play with.&lt;/em&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;As soon as (4) ________ at the park, Sarah spread the blanket on the green grass. They enjoyed their sandwiches and had juicy oranges. After eating, (5) __________ to play with the frisbee.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Buy &lt;/strong&gt;(‡§ñ‡§∞‡•Ä‡§¶‡§®‡§æ): Refers to purchasing, not the act of carrying something along.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Manage &lt;/strong&gt;(‡§™‡•ç‡§∞‡§¨‡§Ç‡§ß ‡§ï‡§∞‡§®‡§æ): Implies control or handling, not relevant here.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Arrange&lt;/strong&gt; (‡§µ‡•ç‡§Ø‡§µ‡§∏‡•ç‡§•‡§ø‡§§ ‡§ï‡§∞‡§®‡§æ): Means to organize or set in order, not suitable for the action of bringing items.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;they arrived&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The sentence refers to a completed action in the past &amp;mdash; Sarah and Tom reaching the park last Sunday.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;They arrived&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; is the correct past simple tense, which matches the rest of the passage that uses past tense consistently.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Options like &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;they arrive&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; (present tense), &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;they had arrive&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; (incorrect verb form), and &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;they was arrive&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; (grammatically incorrect) do not fit the sentence structure or tense.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;Option 3&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;Complete Passage:&lt;i&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;em style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;Sarah and Tom love to go to the park&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;on&lt;/u&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;weekends. Last Sunday, they&amp;nbsp;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;em style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;arranged&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&amp;nbsp;a picnic basket with sandwiches, fruit, and juice. They&amp;nbsp;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;em style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;brought&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;em style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;a blanket to sit on and a frisbee to play with.&lt;/em&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;As soon as &lt;u&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;they arrived&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/u&gt; at the park, Sarah spread the blanket on the green grass. They enjoyed their sandwiches and had juicy oranges. After eating, (5) __________ to play with the frisbee.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;They had arrive&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;ndash; Incorrect past perfect structure; &amp;ldquo;arrive&amp;rdquo; should be &amp;ldquo;arrived&amp;rdquo;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;They arrive&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;ndash; Present tense, incorrect in a past narrative.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;They was arrive&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;ndash; Grammatically incorrect; &amp;ldquo;was&amp;rdquo; should not be used with &amp;ldquo;they&amp;rdquo;, and &amp;ldquo;arrive&amp;rdquo; needs proper conjugation.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;they decided&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The action of choosing to play with the frisbee occurred after eating, in the past, so the verb must be in the simple past tense.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;They decided&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; correctly follows the past tense structure used throughout the passage.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Other options are grammatically incorrect: &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;everyone decide&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; has a subject-verb mismatch, &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;they had decide&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; is incorrect past perfect (should be &amp;quot;had decided&amp;quot;), and &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;they all decide&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; is in present tense.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;Option 4&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;Complete Passage:&lt;i&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;em style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;Sarah and Tom love to go to the park&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;on&lt;/u&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;weekends. Last Sunday, they&amp;nbsp;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;em style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;arranged&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&amp;nbsp;a picnic basket with sandwiches, fruit, and juice. They&amp;nbsp;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;em style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;brought&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;em style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;a blanket to sit on and a frisbee to play with.&lt;/em&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;As soon as&amp;nbsp;&lt;u&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;they arrived&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&amp;nbsp;at the park, Sarah spread the blanket on the green grass. They enjoyed their sandwiches and had juicy oranges. After eating, &lt;u&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;they decided&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/u&gt; to play with the frisbee.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

